    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hiya, chainsafer here, just stumbled upon this issue.\r\n\r\nI think if we use the `BigInt()` syntax instead of bigint literals, in the persistent-merkle-tree dependency, that you should be able to verify the deposit roots here w/o an issue. The persistent-merkle-tree code is only activated when operating on full merkle-tree-backed objects, whereas here we're just using javascript objects. The hashTreeRoot implementation operating on javascript objects doesn't involve gindex calculations or anything else that we're using bigints for, so I don't think we will hit any runtime errors calculating the merkle root.\r\n\r\nOne other thing that would need to change is the use of `BigIntUintType` for the amount.\r\nOne solution would be to use the `NumberUintType`, which will only start overflowing after 3.2M+ Ether (with accounting in gwei), well beyond the practical limit for a single deposit.\r\nAnother solution, we could implement another Uint type using JSBI, BN.js, etc. that can handle the full range of uint64 values w/o using bigint.",
